    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-05T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-05T11:00:00-05:00" n="1354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1354">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">774.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/8–554:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1354<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            type="from">Caffery</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-08-05T18:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 5, 1954—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>167. Although we have in no way encouraged Egyptians to expect huge aid either
                    economic or military they very definitely do expect considerable aid. They have
                    particularly in mind following statement in President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGAD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s letter to <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGM1">Naguib</persName>:<note n="1" xml:id="d1354fn1">The
                        President’s letter was transmitted in telegram 69 to Cairo, <ref
                            target="#d1206">Document 1206</ref>.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“As part of an over-all solution, I am prepared to see firm commitments
                            entered into between our governments to assist you in your plans for
                            Egypt’s economic development and in the strengthening of your armed
                            forces to discharge their increased responsibilities.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FBM1">Fawzi</persName> took occasion to emphasize to me
                    yesterday that whereas they would welcome any aid British might care to give,
                    they wanted it definitely understood that it is our aid they are counting <pb
                        facs="0593" n="2295" xml:id="pg_2295"/> on, and that they assume that any
                    aid British might give would be in addition to our substantial aid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
